<br>
Again, these counter arguments indicate an unfamiliarity with social sciences in general, and with Social Psychology or Anthropology in particular.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Seems like you're missing your own point.  That you, as a mage, immediately recieve tells upon logging in is a fine tribute to your social standing.  Congratulations, etc, here's your cookie.<br>
<br>
I'm guessing these people who hit you up for a group are friends, or people who desperately need a COH'er for a raid, on account of there being almost no magicians online.  I wouldn't believe you if you told me that strangers hit you up for XP groups.  Why would they?  Once we remove the aspect of your personality, there is only your class, and your class is not as good as a lot of more highly available ones.<br>
<br>
Now if you played one of the Holy Trinity, you really would have strangers hunt for you asking if you want to join.  I hunt for strangers to groups all the time.  Mostly clerics, but sometimes warriors, rogues and enchanters as well.  Even druids and shaman if I can't find a cleric.  Never mages.  Even if I wasn't a mage, I still would never hunt for a strange mage to group with me.  Aside from being a dangerous class if the player isn't competent, it's simply not as useful as more available alternatives.  Even if the mage was right in front of me, I would frankly rather wait for a rogue or just take a wizard, because at least the wizard makes it easy to evac to the zoneline when the group wants to break.<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ugrumples.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grumples</A> at: 3/25/02 2:46:50 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=falinkrin>Falinkrin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mage</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#333333>(3/25/02 3:53:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=163.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Grouping IS a social issue!</span><hr size=1> A.   Build groups.  Not only will you have control of your playing time, but you will gain skills that are just flat invaluable to a guild.  Finding someone who can handle even a Group Leader position on a raid is tough.<br>
<br>
B.  Forget the standard xp group crap.  If you sit around looking for a cleric, warrior and enchanter for your group then you will sit a lot, and when the group is formed they won't be happy with you being there.  Try a ranger, rogue, shammy, bard, etc.  Feel your way into the first few pulls, and encourage folks to play around a bit to find out what works.  All that is really required of a group is some type of healing, some type of melee, some type of damage, and some type of crowd control (root works, dont forget it).  <br>
<br>
C.  Get the heck out of the crowded zones.  If there are four or more people LFG, and you can't get them to form up a group, then leave.  Go somewhere else.<br>
<br>
Nonstandard groups are mucho fun, and making them work will make you a very popular person. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ugrumples.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grumples</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 510<br> <font color=#333333>(3/25/02 4:05:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=163.topic&index=23>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Grouping IS a social issue!</span><hr size=1> And if the classes were better balanced, that would be unnecessary.<br>
