It does not eliminate perception or stereotypes of classes, group styles or perceived roles as issues. All social issues.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Your confusing me now. As a mage I cannot control 3 adds. As a mage I cannot cast a spell that doubles everyone's mana regen. As a mage I cannot Main Tank for the Group. As a mage I cannot pull in many situations. How is this perception? The flaw in your argument is that you believe there is some stereotype or perception issue here. There is not. Our only role is to deal damage in your classic group. And the reality of the matter is there are very few positions open in classic styled groups for a class that can only do damage. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> This is not Social.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
I could agree with you if you were to change your position some. I could agree with you if you were saying: You have to use a great deal of social skills to overcome the lack of role that Magicians currently have, because a magician's core abilities are not that attractive to your classic grouping setup.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> I would agree that the solution is Social but not the problem itself.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Nandail<br>
