<br>
During the rare times I want to group with my mage, I am grouping with my friends' alts.  Frankly, I made my mage knowing this-Warriors are almost completely dependent upon groups and I get sick of that.  My Mage is my selfish character, my Warrior is my grouping character, and my Druid is my selfless character that I basically use for running around lower level areas healing and buffing. <br>
<br>
I can tell you this:  it is absolutely true that Mages and Wizards are passed over for groups.  If i have to choose a Cleric over a Mage or Wizard as my Warrior I am darned well going to pick the Cleric, because the Cleric will keep me alive.  If I have to choose between the Mage and the Wizard, I will take the Wizard because he can tl, and put out an immense amount of damage, plus he can root, making him a little more effective at crowd control.  Now, think what you like, but this is an honest post from someone who plays a mage; though maybe not as high level as most of you.<br>
<br>
Though I am unsure what VI's vision was when they created the Mage, what I see is a class that predominately solos, is designed to be better solo than in group, and who's skills have been watered down.  I, for one, look avidly forward to the &quot;class balancing&quot; in the hopes they get off the fence in regard to mages--either we are a soloing class or a grouping class, but I think that trying to make them both is making them too weak in each department.<br>
<br>
Keep the change.<br>
<br>
