Tarew Marr</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 1075<br> <font color=#333333>(3/26/02 5:52:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=163.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Difficulty with grouping in 50+ or just cause I am a mag</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Our only role is to deal damage in your classic group<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->The <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;classic group&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and its associated roles, is a social construct.  I, and many others, chose to construct other types of groups, with a different set of roles.<br>
<br>
I am often the puller, so much so I am relieved when someone else volunteers.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is often the main tank.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I wouldn't believe you if you told me that strangers hit you up for XP groups.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->As I've said, I build groups, I don't <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> LFG</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and I generally only group with strangers when someone I know invites me to a group that includes people I do not know.  I don't like putting myself at the mercy of players of unknown ability or temperment, where I lack control, and where, if I am uncomfortable with someone, my only choice is to leave.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> your class is not as good as a lot of more highly available ones.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This is a matter of some dispute.  I am not the only poster who believes that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are pretty good in experience groups.  While I agree that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are not popular, either to play or to invite, I maintain that this says more about players' perceptions than any objective weakness of the class.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The flaw in your argument is that you believe there is some stereotype or perception issue here. There is not. Our only role is to deal damage in your classic group. And the reality of the matter is there are very few positions open in classic styled groups for a class that can only do damage. This is not Social.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>very</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> social.<br>
<br>
First of all, the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;classic group&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is entirely a social construct, as are the roles within it.  Objectively, there are only two requirements for an experience group.  First, the mob must die in order to yield experience, so damage dealing is necessary.  Second, you must avoid dying yourself, so damage mitigation is the other role.  Kill, not get killed yourself.<br>
<br>
These are the <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>only</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> necessary roles for a group.<br>
<br>
Various group styles are all different means of accomplishing this.  For example, in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Area of Effect</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> groups, damage dealing is done in the obvious way, and damage mitigation is primarily through stun, and to a lesser extent, pets.<br>
<br>
In my prefered playing style, pets tank, and act as the damage mitigators.  No player required to tank, and healers, while nice, are hardly necessary.  It's only when a player tank gets involved that I have to change styles and worry about them dying.  If it is just pets, well perhaps <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s brother <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Jibaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> will do better.<br>
<br>
The classic group setting is simply one popular style of play, and judging classes solely against that style is not in the least objective.  The classic group IS a stereotype.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Now if you played one of the Holy Trinity, you really would have strangers hunt for you asking if you want to join.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Death to the Holy Trinity!  Long Live the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub6.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showMessage?topicID=3824.topic">The UnHoly Trinity</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->!<br>
<br>
When a stereotyped playing style <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (&quot;classic&quot; group)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> yields stereotyped results <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (Mages are not wanted)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, it is a mistake to elevate the stereotype to an objective truth.<br>
<br>
What you really have here are unexamined assumptions.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Raz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/usuzannadreamingheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SuzannaDreamingheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#333333>(3/26/02 4:39:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=163.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Difficulty with grouping in 50+ or just cause I am a mag</span><hr size=1> What is this? School for social scientists to pontificate on their navals? Utter nonsense.<br>
<br>
The original poster is correct. It is the experience of *almost all* mages. Mages ARE less desirable in groups. It's just a fact, not a social commentary. Hell, I know well, my alt is a 60 Cleric, and I won't take an unknown mage over an unknown rogue or monk, they are just are not in the same league TECHNICALLY (social sense is IRRELEVANT).<br>
<br>
However, most players, including me, group with friends over strangers, regardless of class. So Suzanna gets groups, with friends, and my cleric will group happily with mage friends. This is normal. And when Suzanna can't get a group, she solos until friends come online.<br>
<br>
But to anyone who uses social science claptrap to talk riddles round the OBVIOUS FACT that clerics and enchanters find groups with strangers far easier than Mages and Wizards are talking out of their rears, and let's face it, we all know it.<br>
<br>
